04286nam a22006375i 9783110746860DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212022gw     fo  d z      eng d  a2021947720  a97831107468607 a10.1515/97831107468602doi  a(DE-B1597)579694  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE1 aLorenz, Peter E., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut12aA History of Codex Bezae’s Text in the Gospel of Mark /cPeter E. Lorenz. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2021] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (XVI, 1013 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aArbeiten zur neutestamentlichen Textforschung ,x0570-5509 ;v5300tFrontmatter -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tChapter A: The Date of Codex Bezae’s Greek Text -- tChapter 2: Codex Bezae’s Greek Text and the Latin Version -- tChapter 3: Greek-Latin Bilingualism in Codex Bezae’s Production Context -- tChapter 4: Modeling Textual Change in the Development of Codex Bezae’s Greek Text -- tChapter 5: The Production Context of Codex Bezae’s Text of Mark -- tChapter 6: The Latin Layer of Codex Bezae’s Greek Text of Mark -- tChapter 7: Codex Bezae’s Text of Mark and the Greek Tradition -- tChapter 8: Towards a Textual History of Codex Bezae in Mark -- tAppendix 1: List of Witnesses -- tAppendix 2: Classification of Greek Witnesses in Mark -- tBibliography of Works Cited -- tIndex of Ancient Works -- tGeneral Index0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAs the principal Greek witness of the so-called "Western" tradition of the gospels and Acts, Codex Bezae’s enigmatic text in parallel Greek and Latin columns presents a persistent problem of New Testament textual criticism. The present study challenges the traditional view that this text represents a vivid retelling of the canonical narratives cited by ancient writers from Justin Martyr to Marcion and translated early into Syriac and Latin.  aUsing a combination of text-critical, church-historical, philological, and digital methods, the present study calls into question traditional assumptions about Codex Bezae’s distinctive Greek text of the gospels and Acts — that it represents an ancient native Greek tradition and source of the Latin version preserving a textual relic of the first century of Christianity — arguing that this text can be credibly dated to the end of the fourth century, immediately preceding production of the manuscript, and represents the diorthosis of a Greek text to a Latin model distinct from the Latin column found in the manuscript itself. So the better part of this remarkable text derives ultimately from other traditions and, hence, its true significance lies in what it can tell us about the historical circumstances under which the manuscript and its final text were produced at the turn of the fifth century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 4aMarkusevangelium. 4aNeues Testament. 4aPaläographie. 4aTextkritik.0 cEPUBz97831107469380 cprintz978311074605140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978311074686040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783110746860423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9783110746860/original  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_DGALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK